IRS990.ActivityOrMissionDescription: Lakeland College provides educational services to undergraduate and graduate students in Sheboygan County and throughout Wisconsin. The fees collected directly relate to the provision of those services on a one-to-one basis (i.e., this revenue is collected from the beneficiaries of the service.) In addition, housing and meal services are provided to the students attending classes at the main campus. Living in the campus community is an integral part of a traditional 4 year liberal arts educations, which Lakeland College provides in its traditional Day-undergraduate program.

ASSET RETIREMENT OBLIGATIONS: Asset retirement obligations (ARO) are estimated costs and obligations associated with the retirement of long-lived assets. These liabilities are initially recorded at fair value and the related asset retirement costs are recorded as decreases in unrestricted net assets. Asset retirement costs are subsequently accreted over the useful lives of the related assets. The estimate of the losses that are probably from environmental remediation liabilities for asbestos removal was calculated using the expected cash flow approach and based on an inventory of the College's long-lived assets combined with an estimate of the current market prices to remove the asbestos. The College utilized a credit-adjusted risk-free rate to discount the asset retirement obligation. It is reasonably possible that changes in this estimate could occur and that actual results could differ from this estimate and could have a significant effect on the financial statements.

AcctsActvsOutUSTable.SpecificServicesProvided: Educate students selected by Agency for International Development (A.I.D.) to become teachers and professors of education in Malawi. Lakeland also provides funding to help the Malawi ministry of Education and Lakeland's program graduates to build rural schools.

Lakeland College has a partnership with a Japanese entity (NIC) to operate a campus in Tokyo which offers courses identical to those offered in our Sheboygan, Wisconsin campus and grants a U.S. accredited associate of arts degree. Gross revenues are collected and expenses paid by NIC. Lakeland College provides academic oversight and shares in any net income through this program.

Form990ScheduleFPartIV.Explanation: Professor Jeff Elzinga, who is a former U.S. State Department Consular Official in Malawi, and is a Lakeland College Professor, reviews grant applications and approves payments only upon receipt of expense documentation. Lakeland faculty visit Malawi every other year and review the projects and programs associated with the grants given. Recipients are all graduates of Lakeland's A.I.D. Affiliated Malawi Teacher Education Program and are constructing schools in Malawi under the auspices of that country's ministry of education.
